article.description: The first playoff game for the Minnesota Lynx may have been the most shocking in WNBA history.
article.headline: Lynx end 16-game skid against Sparks

images.name: Williams Tamika 030828 horz inline
images.caption: Tamika Williams, right, went up for this rebound, but it was her steal and layup that clinched the win.

article.linkText: Lynx rally from 21 down to stun Sparks
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Williams won it for Minnesota with her last-second steal, but Lisa Leslie felt the game was stolen from Los Angeles long before that.
Thursday, Aug. 28
Heading into the playoffs, Los Angeles didn't have a lot of depth and was susceptible to foul trouble and injuries. That's exactly what got the Sparks in trouble Thursday. The Sparks seemed to have the game in hand after the break, but then Lisa Leslie picked up her fifth foul and sat out much of the second half. Minnesota was already starting to gain some momentum at the time, and when Leslie left, Katie Smith took over. Her 3-pointer to tie the score at 72 on a fade out of the timeout was a great shot, and Smith, one of the top 10 players in the world, deserves a lot of credit for hitting it. But that was just simply a poor defensive stance from L.A., which left Smith completely wide open. The Lynx deserve a lot of credit for the comeback, using a nice, balanced effort. But Leslie's absence -- the Sparks are a much better defensive team with her on the floor -- in the second half hurt. And L.A.'s backcourt obviously wasn't at its best with Nikki Teasley and backup Shaquala Williams both injured, and role player Nicky McCrimmon, who is averages 9.1 minutes, asked to pick up the slack. The Sparks can still win this series, especially with Game 2 -- and Game 3 if necessary -- in L.A. But the Sparks will struggle to move on if Teasley can't return and the team's starters -- particularly Leslie -- continue to battle foul trouble. And remember this -- though Teasley is said to have a bruised knee, that's the same vague diagnosis that kept Leslie out for 11 games after the All-Star break.
Now, the two-time defending champion Sparks find themselves on the brink of elimination. Williams stole a pass and scored with 7 seconds left as Minnesota opened the WNBA playoffs by overcoming a 21-point deficit and stunning the Sparks 74-72 Thursday night in the largest comeback in playoff history. "We had a guy in the stands have a heart attack today," Williams said, referring to a fan that was hospitalized during the game. "That's how exciting the game was." "Katie (Smith) and I both played 40 minutes. It takes everything to beat a team of this caliber." According to Leslie, it took even more than that. "I felt the game was played very unfairly," she said. "I know it's on the road and you're not always going to get the calls, but that's all I can really say about this situation." When asked if she was calling out the referees, Leslie responded, "You have to interpret it however you want." Ten fouls were called on Los Angeles in the first 10 minutes of the second half. "It was a tough game to be played, shooting free throws every minute," Leslie said. "Definitely not a good game for women's basketball." Still, Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper said, "We can't blame injuries or foul trouble. Those five Lynx players, no matter who was out there, were playing harder and better than us in the second half." Minnesota -- which had lost 16 straight to the Sparks dating to their first meeting in 1999 -- visits Los Angeles on Saturday night in the second game of the best-of-three Western Conference series. Smith scored 23 points for Minnesota. Williams added 16 points and six rebounds, and reserve Kristi Harrower had eight points and five assists. "I think it was just aggressiveness," Smith said of the biggest comeback in Lynx history. "We picked up full-court and made different people handle the ball." Despite her foul trouble, Leslie had 24 points and seven rebounds for the Sparks, who had lost only one other playoff game during their two-year title run. Tamecka Dixon, also in foul trouble, scored 18 points and Mwadi Mabika had 15. "Instead of trying to play to win, we played not to lose," Cooper said. "Great game, though, I had a great seat." Los Angeles' starting point guard Nikki Teasley went down with a left-knee contusion midway through the first half. She stayed down for a few minutes before being helped off the court by trainers. The team evaluated Teasley at halftime and decided to not to play her in the second half. After the game, she was taken to a local hospital for X-rays, which were negative. She is day-to-day and will undergo an MRI exam when the team returns to Los Angeles. "This is the playoffs, and now we're down one," Teasley said. "Nothing is going to keep me from playing and helping the team win." Mabika made a layup with 1:22 left to give Los Angeles a 70-69 lead, and Leslie took over on the next two possessions. First she blocked Williams' layup attempt and then scored on a jump hook to make it 72-69. Smith hit a 3-pointer with 24 seconds left to tie the game again before Williams' game-winning play. Mabika was inbounding the ball at half-court when Williams stole it, drove the length of the court and hit a layup while being fouled. She missed the foul shot, but Los Angeles could not get a shot up on the other end as time expired. "It was nothing big," Williams said, recalling that she often made plays like it in high school and college. "It wasn't like I was in another world, it was just basketball." The final margin was Minnesota's largest lead of the game. Trailing by 21 points in the second half, the Lynx went on a 21-6 run to close within 59-53 with 7:58 left. As a team, Minnesota made nine of 11 free throws during the stretch and was helped when both Leslie and Dixon picked up a fifth foul with just over 10 minutes left. "I just think it's sad for the game of women's basketball the way the second half went," Leslie said.
